    <h2 class="date-header">October 20, 2013</h2>

	<div class="entry-category-books entry-category-technical entry-author-brad_wilson entry-type-post entry" id="entry-6a00e54fbd8c498834019b002b75a4970d">
       <div class="entry-inner">
					<h3 class="entry-header"><a href="https://bradwilson.typepad.com/blog/2013/10/book-review-net-45-parallel-extensions-cookbook.html">Book Review: .NET 4.5 Parallel Extensions Cookbook</a></h3>
		



		<div class="entry-content">

			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><em><strong>Disclosure:</strong> I was offered a free electronic copy of this book in exchange for this book review. The publisher had no input on the review.</em></p>
<p>Parallel processing is one of the most challenging problems for the modern developer. The first time you start creating threads, you open yourself up to a whole host of problems, including deadlocks and data corruption. The ASP.NET team went to great lengths to hide all the difficulties of multi-threading by presenting a programming model that allows developers to reap the benefits of multi-threading without sweating most of the details. Similarly, the Task Parallel Library – introduced in .NET 4, and greatly improved in .NET 4.5 – attempts to bring that same level of abstraction without diving deep into the threading details.</p>

