					<h3 class="entry-header"><a href="https://bradwilson.typepad.com/blog/2012/06/batching-handler-for-web-api.html">Batching Handler for ASP.NET Web API</a></h3>
		



		<div class="entry-content">

			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><strong><em>Update: The Web API team is planning to <a href="https://aspnetwebstack.codeplex.com/wikipage?title=Web+API+Request+Batching" target="_self">add this to v2</a>. Please visit the Wiki and give feedback!<br /></em></strong></p>
<p>While there is no batching standard built into the HTTP protocol, there is a standard for MIME encoding HTTP request and response messages (&quot;application/http&quot; with &quot;msgtype=request&quot; and &quot;msgtype=response&quot;, respectively). ASP.NET Web API has built-in support for both MIME multipart as well as encoded request and response messages, so we have all the building blocks we need to make a simple batch request handler.</p>

